title: For Sale:  Beretta 92F 9mm
postcontent: This is an Italian made 92F. It was not made by Beretta USA for the Army M9 or 92FS civilian market. The Army adopted the 92FS in 1985, after changes were made to the 92F to make it safer after the Navy used machine gun bullets during testing causing the slide to fail, and reissued it as the M9. So, this is an early to mid 80's, used Italian Beretta 92F 9mm with factory walnut checkered grips with Beretta logo inserts. Serial # starts with 'C'. But, since this is an Italian gun, you won't find the serial # on Beretta USA. You have to go to "Catalogo Nazionale Armi" which is the records of all Beretta Italian produced guns. The Italian bank proof marks the gun somewhere, in this case on the right side trigger guard, and puts a Date Code. The date code on this is AN which equals 1985, before the Army gave them the contract and they changed to the 92FS in 1985. So, basically this is the last issue of the Beretta 92F. There are three handguns in the world that combine, quality, beauty, and reliability making them the finest handguns in the world today. They are: Colt Python .357, Colt 1991A1 Commander .45 acp, and the Beretta 92F 9mm. This is your chance to own one of them as they have rolled off of the CA Gun Roster. Comes with two 15 rd. magazines, and original plastic box. I would rate the pistol finish at 98% as there is no holster wear, scratches, etc. The only finish wear is some slight wear around the safety/decocker. It has had about 500 rounds through it and then kept in climate controlled safe after I stopped shooting. Comes with two Magblocks to make the mags 10 rd capacity to meet CA compliance in July. No paperwork or cardboard box as I left them along with several others in the attic during a move many years back. :-( This is a very nice shooter that's just getting broken in. Smooth trigger pull, accurate, and a pleasure to handle. I like this almost as much as my Colt Python. But, the Colt's not for sale. lol I have two of these. I picked up a second one while I was living in Denver for work, but still had my house here. Just don't need two of them anymore. Would consider a trade with my gun plus money for a Sig Sauer P225A1 9mm or a Beretta 85FS Cheetah .380. Not interested in any other guns... Thanks for looking. NO SHIPPING! Private party transactions must take place face to face at a current FFL dealer per CA law and in my area. I am totally disabled and will not travel outside of Sacramento, CA.  SERIOUS offers only. Don't lowball me because it's your 'birthday' or offer me a used XBOX to trade. If you can't make the deal by providing money or the guns I mentioned above, then don't bother me. Price is $650 OBO firm. Thanks!

title: For Sale:  AR15 Barrel Spline wrench (Reaction Rod)
postcontent: Used AR15 barrel spline wrench, in good condition shows some normal finish wear from normal use, but nothing that will affect function. This is by far the best method for changing your AR15 barrel or muzzle device, only selling because I have a few and don't need the extras. Asking $50, can meet in the Green Bay areaA great tool that securely holds an upper receiver assembly for maintenance and assembly work. The removal and installation of barrels, flash hiders, gas blocks and hand guards is made much easier and simpler.Designed to be gripped in a bench vise so that the rod is either horizontal or vertical. The upper receiver is then slid onto the rod and the rod’s integral splines enter the barrel extension and secure the barrel extension from turning.This allows all the torque from barrel nut wrenches to go directly into the barrel extension. The receiver vise blocks transmit the turning force into the aluminum receiver, a good part of which passes through the small, easily distorted receiver index pin. With the Barrel Spline Socket Rod, marring of an upper receiver’s finish by gripping and twisting inside vise blocks is eliminated and so is the need to remove sights and mounts from the receiver’s M1913 rail.
